I did more tests and found that the problem may be caused by such pattern: quant-dequant in chain
![_A6CVLP)GXGU XM{)X7ETAQ](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6896966/206634184-8c7b291e-38ea-42ae-8189-c3d6642e4bb6.png)

@shalvamist

another xnnpack correctness issue. There are possibly problems with quantization implementation in web assembly build.

Hey @vacing,

Sorry for the late response, I have been backlogged on a few issues.
I have reviewed the issue you reported and tried to run the model in python but couldn't - I got an error when I try to run the model on random data. [Please see this colab notebook](https://colab.research.google.com/gist/shalvamist/784e277b9f679d040bd6be90660a2ff3/model_load_issue_13912.ipynb)
I think I might be running the model with incorrect inputs or there might be an issue with the model itself. Can you please share a way to reproduce the issue you reported ?

Thanks

> 

some input of the model has no input shape, you can specify the input shape of the model like this
```python
shapes = {
    "src": [1, 3, 160, 180],
    "r1i": [1, 16, 80, 90],
    "r2i": [1, 20, 40, 45],  
    "r3i": [1, 40, 20, 23],  
    "r4i": [1, 64, 10, 12],
}
feeds = {}
for input_meta in sess.get_inputs():
    name = input_meta.name
    shape = shapes[name]
    gen_one_input(feeds, name, shape, input_meta.type)

for f in feeds:
  print(feeds[f].shape)
```

OK cool - thanks for the info. I can run the model in python now.
I will try to reproduce the problem in ORT Web - I will keep you posted with and finding I might have.

It's because a DQ node shared by more than one consumer nodes.

This model has dynamic shape, so shape can not  be determinated if input is unknow and shape inference failed netither. I guess onnx.checker.check_model only works for static model.

For this issue, just comment `onnx.checker.check_model(model)` in the function.
